def create_fake_data(N, M, case="DD"):
    """
    Creates synthetic dataset with N samples and M features.
    
    case: "DD"  → Categorical features & categorical target
          "DR"  → Categorical features & continuous target
          "RD"  → Continuous features & categorical target
          "RR"  → Continuous features & continuous target
    """
    if case == "DD":
        # Classification: categorical X and y
        X = pd.DataFrame({f"f{i}": pd.Series(np.random.randint(0, 5, size=N), dtype="category") for i in range(M)})
        y = pd.Series(np.random.randint(0, 5, size=N), dtype="category")
    
    elif case == "DR":
        # Regression: categorical X, continuous y
        X = pd.DataFrame({f"f{i}": pd.Series(np.random.randint(0, 5, size=N), dtype="category") for i in range(M)})
        y = pd.Series(np.random.randn(N))
    
    elif case == "RD":
        # Classification: continuous X, categorical y
        X = pd.DataFrame({f"f{i}": np.random.randn(N) for i in range(M)})
        y = pd.Series(np.random.randint(0, 5, size=N), dtype="category")
    
    elif case == "RR":
        # Regression: continuous X, continuous y
        X = pd.DataFrame({f"f{i}": np.random.randn(N) for i in range(M)})
        y = pd.Series(np.random.randn(N))
    
    else:
        raise ValueError("Invalid case. Choose from 'DD', 'DR', 'RD', 'RR'.")
    
    return X, y

    • Measure the time taken for:
      1. Learning the decision tree

def measure_runtime(N, M, case="DD", max_depth=5, num_runs=10):
    
    X, y = create_fake_data(N, M, case)
    
    fit_times = []
    pred_times = []
    
    for _ in range(num_runs):
        tree = DecisionTree(criterion=case, max_depth=max_depth, save_plot=False)
        
        # Measure fit time
        start = time.time()
        tree.fit(X, y)
        fit_times.append(time.time() - start)
        
        # Measure predict time
        start = time.time()
        y_hat = tree.predict(X)
        pred_times.append(time.time() - start)
    
    avg_fit_time = np.mean(fit_times)
    avg_pred_time = np.mean(pred_times)
    
    print(f"Case: {case}, N={N}, M={M}, max_depth={max_depth}")
    print(f"Average fit time: {avg_fit_time:.6f} sec")
    print(f"Average predict time: {avg_pred_time:.6f} sec\n")
    
    return avg_fit_time, avg_pred_time

def measure_runtime_and_plot(N_list, M_list, cases=["DD","DR","RD","RR"], num_trials=5):
    results = {case: {"fit": [], "predict": []} for case in cases}

    for case in cases:
        for N in N_list:
            for M in M_list:
                X, y = create_fake_data(N, M, case)
                tree = DecisionTree(criterion=case, max_depth=5, save_plot=False)
                
                # Fit time
                fit_times = []
                for _ in range(num_trials):
                    start = time.time()
                    tree.fit(X, y)
                    fit_times.append(time.time() - start)
                avg_fit = np.mean(fit_times)
                
                # Predict time
                predict_times = []
                for _ in range(num_trials):
                    start = time.time()
                    _ = tree.predict(X)
                    predict_times.append(time.time() - start)
                avg_pred = np.mean(predict_times)
                
                results[case]["fit"].append((N, M, avg_fit))
                results[case]["predict"].append((N, M, avg_pred))

    return results

# Example usage:
N_list = [50, 100, 200, 400]
M_list = [2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 20]

results = measure_runtime_and_plot(N_list, M_list)

cases = ["DD", "DR", "RD", "RR"]

for case in cases:
    times_fit = results[case]["fit"]
    times_pred = results[case]["predict"]

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 5))
    fig.suptitle(f"Decision Tree Runtime for {case} Case")

    # Fit time plot
    for M in M_list:
        filtered = [t for t in times_fit if t[1] == M]
        axs[0].plot(
            [t[0] for t in filtered],
            [t[2] for t in filtered],
            marker="o",
            label=f"M={M}",
        )
    axs[0].set_xlabel("Number of Samples N")
    axs[0].set_ylabel("Average Fit Time (s)")
    axs[0].set_title("Training Time")
    axs[0].legend()

    # Predict time plot
    for M in M_list:
        filtered = [t for t in times_pred if t[1] == M]
        axs[1].plot(
            [t[0] for t in filtered],
            [t[2] for t in filtered],
            marker="o",
            label=f"M={M}",
        )
    axs[1].set_xlabel("Number of Samples N")
    axs[1].set_ylabel("Average Predict Time (s)")
    axs[1].set_title("Prediction Time")
    axs[1].legend()

    plt.show()

    • Compare the observed runtime with the theoretical time complexity for:
      • Decision tree creation
      • Decision tree prediction

2. Your Results vs. Theory¶

DD & DR: The fit time increases roughly in a linear fashion with the number of features M; for example, with 50 samples, the time rises from 0.07 to 0.79 seconds as M increases from 2 to 10. It also grows with the number of samples N which is expected O(NlogN) behavior.

RD & RR: The fit time is not as expected may be because of the continuous splitting we are doing inside it.
